{"cursor":"4299","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox philosopher\n| region = Western Philosophy era = 20th-century philosophy image = caption =\n| signature = name = Knud Ejler LÃ¸gstrup birth_date = 2 September 1905\n| birth_place = Copenhagen, Denmark death_date = death_place = school_tradition\n| = Continental philosophy main_interests = Philosophy of religion,\n| Phenomenology, Ethics influences = Martin Heidegger, Luther, Kant,\n| Kierkegaard, Lipps, Toulmin influenced = Zygmunt Bauman notable_ideas = the\n| 'ethical demand,' the 'sovereign expressions of life'\n}}\n\n'Knud Ejler LÃ¸gstrup' (1905â1981) was a Danish philosopher and theologian.\n\nLÃ¸gstrup was an ethical intuitionist who was critical of rule-based ethics of\nthe type advocated by Immanuel Kant. In other words, he disliked ethical systems\nwhich try to determine basic moral laws.\n\nLÃ¸gstrup mentions philosopher Stephen Toulmin's example of an everyday\nsituation: \"I have borrowed a book from John and the question is now, why should\nI give it back today as I promised him?\", Toulmin asks in order to derive more\ngeneral moral rules. But if I give John back his book because \"I should always\nkeep my promises\" or because of the more general rule \"I should never lie\", I\ntreat him as a means; this is unethical, as well. In the 1930es LÃ¸gstrup was a\npart of the Tidehverv movement in Danish theology which at the time espoused a\ndialectical theology, he left the movement in the early 1950s.\n\nMorality is not about rules, but about the so-called 'sovereign expressions of\nlife'. All men have an intuitive feeling of right and wrong. 'Sovereign\nexpressions of life' includes feelings and actions as open speech, trust,\ncompassion, mercy, and love. These phenomena are intrinsically good. A good\nexample is open speech. Even when secret police are searching an apartment, the\npeople living there cannot help but speak with the police sergeant, because it\nfeels intuitively natural to do so.\n\nMoral laws are only substitutes for intuition in situations where these\nintuitive feelings fails to lead to action. For instance, the Golden rule is a\nsubstitute for compassion.\n\nSo, LÃ¸gstrup takes the opposite point of view to Kant, who believed that moral\nlaws are the only truly moral basis for action, and that natural desires can\nnever be moral.\n","linknr":137,"url":"Knud_Ejler_Løgstrup","recorded":1375076096,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Knud_Ejler_L%C3%B8gstrup&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Knud_Ejler_L%C3%B8gstrup&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Copenhagen","/wiki/Denmark","/wiki/20th-century_philosophy","/wiki/List_of_schools_of_philosophy","/wiki/Continental_philosophy","/wiki/Philosophy_of_religion","/wiki/Phenomenology_(philosophy)","/wiki/Ethics_(philosophy)","/wiki/Martin_Heidegger","/wiki/Martin_Luther","/wiki/Immanuel_Kant","/wiki/S%C3%B8ren_Kierkegaard","/wiki/Hans_Lipps","/wiki/Stephen_Toulmin","/wiki/Zygmunt_Bauman","/wiki/Denmark","/wiki/Philosophy","/wiki/Theology","/wiki/Ethical_intuitionism","/wiki/Ethics","/wiki/Immanuel_Kant","/wiki/Moral","/wiki/Stephen_Toulmin","/wiki/Tidehverv","/wiki/Dialectical_theology","/wiki/Intuition_(know